sentences: Jeanne Baxtresser (born August 2, 1947) is an American flutist and teacher.

She is most notable for her position as principal flutist of the New York Philharmonic for over 15 years, she decided to play the flute when she was only nine years old, as an author (Orchestral Excerpts for Flute with Piano Accompaniment), and as a professor and master teacher.

She received the National Flute Association's Lifetime Achievement Award in 2006.
Jeanne Baxtresser was born August 2, 1947 in Bethlehem, Pennsylvania to Earl and Margaret (Barthel) Baxtresser.
During these years, Baxtresser also attended the Interlochen National Music Camp and Academy as a flute pupil of Gary Sigurdson.
Baxtresser auditioned and was accepted into the Juilliard School of Music in New York City, starting in 1965.

She studied with Julius Baker for four years, working with many of the influential composers and colleagues of the time, including conductor Leonard Slatkin, and pianists Emanuel Ax, Garrick Ohlsson, and Jeffrey Siegle.

During her final year at Juilliard, Baxtresser won the position of Principal Flutist of the Montreal Symphony in 1969, and shortly after was hired as professor of flute at McGill University in Montreal.

She was subsequently appointed Principal Flute of the Toronto Symphony Orchestra in 1976, before being invited by Music Director Zubin Mehta to join the New York Philharmonic in 1981.

She retired from the New York Philharmonic in 1998, to focus on full time teaching.
